# Source material. Not for publishing.
#
# The rule is simple and it is not risk-based: sources/ holds the documents the site was
# WRITTEN FROM, and those are private. Project READMEs, course reports, portfolio PDFs,
# presentation decks, raw and superseded media. They are inputs. The site publishes what
# was written from them, not them.
#
# So the test for a new file is not "is this sensitive." It is "does a card display this."
# If a card displays it, it belongs in assets/. If it is something the writing drew on,
# it belongs here, regardless of how harmless it looks.
#
# assets/ is served verbatim by GitHub Pages, so anything there is publicly downloadable
# at a guessable URL. That is what makes the distinction load-bearing rather than tidy.
# It matters most for the MoonRanger portfolio PDF, which contains flight software detail
# the site's copy deliberately stays above, but that is a consequence of the rule, not the
# reason for it.
#
# Keep source material here. Do not move it back into assets/.
sources/

# Working material kept out of the repo entirely. content/ holds the raw project
# notes (including the MoonRanger "withheld on confidentiality grounds" index) and the
# finished copy; voice/ holds Arnav's personal writing samples. The site is built from
# these but does not need them at runtime, and on a public repo they would be browsable.
# The built site in docs/ is unaffected. Kept local, not pushed.
content/
voice/

# OS / editor noise
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
desktop.ini
